[[File:Imoyama (Yoshino), enkei.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|View of Imosayama from the opposite bank}}{{small|The torii gate of Daimamochi Shrine is on the center left. In the foreground is [[Yoshino River (Nara Prefecture)|Yoshino River]]. }}]]
``Dainamochi Shrine'' is located in Kawaraya, {{ill|lt=Nara Prefecture|Q131287|WD=Q131287|1=Nara Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Yoshino District|Q1154558|WD=Q1154558|1=Yoshino District, Nara}}{{ill|lt=Yoshino Town|Q1203731|WD=Q1203731|1=Yoshino, Nara}}. It is {{ill|UNKNOWN|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikiuchi|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286|lt=Shikinaisha}} ({{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}}), and {{ill|lt=Modern shrine rank system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|lt=Old shrine rank|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}} is {{ill|lt=Gosha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}}. It is also commonly known as ``Daigo Shrine''.{{Sfn|Dainamochi Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}} is located near the junction of the former {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Ise Kaido|1=UNKNOWN}} and the former Higashi-Kumano Kaido, at the foot of the independent peak {{ill|lt=Mt. Imose (Nara Prefecture)|Q112339073|WD=Q112339073|lt=Imoseyama|1=Imoseyama}}.

=== Enshrined God ===
The following three deities are enshrined. </ref>.
* {{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|lt=Daimyochimitamokami|1=Ōkuninushi}}
* {{ill|lt=Suseribime|Q8191715|WD=Q8191715|lt=Suserihime no Mikoto|1=Suseri-Hime}}
* {{ill|lt=Sukunabikona|Q3275687|WD=Q3275687|lt=Shonahikona no Mikoto|1=Sukunabikona}}
In the literature, there is ``Daimomichi Shrine'' in ``{{ill|lt=Japan Three Dynasties Annals|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}'', ``Dainamochi Shrine'' in ``{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}'', and ``Engishiki'' extraordinary festival. It is seen as the ``Daimyochimitama Shrine Troupe'' in the Meishin Festival, and the enshrined deity has been one of the troupes of Onamuchi (another name for Okuninushi ({{ill|lt=Ōkuninushi|Q276944|WD=Q276944|1=Ōkuninushi}})).

It is not clear how Sukunabikona (Shona Hikona) was enshrined as a deity, but it was later named after a poem in volume 7 of "{{ill|lt=Manyoshu|Q834321|WD=Q834321|1=Man'yōshū}}" (see below). There is a theory that it is a joint enshrinement of the gods, and another that it is the god of the mountain on the opposite bank. Furthermore, in the "Shinja Detailed Book", there are four deities enshrined: Daimyomochi-kami, Daimyochimitama-kami, the concubine Suserihime-kami, and Shunahikomakami.

=== History ===

=== Outline ===
Founding date is unknown. {{ill|lt=Shisetsu (Nara Prefecture)|Q112339073|WD=Q112339073|lt=Imoyamajuso|1=Imoseyama}} (249 meters above sea level<ref name="Imoyamajuso">[http://www.town.yoshino.nara.jp/kanko-event/meisho-kanko/shisetsu/ryumon-nakaryumon/imoyamajuso.html Imosayama is also called ``Imiyama,'' and it is said to be a sacred mountain because there is a taboo belief against cutting down trees to this day. k|Shintaiyama|Q1595289}} {{ill|lt=animism|Q43004|WD=Q43004|lt=primitive faith|1=Animism}} is presumed to be the founding shrine {{Sfn|Dainamochi Shrine (gods)|2000}}.In {{ill|lt=Rokukokushi|Q1151168|WD=Q1151168|lt=Kokukushi|1=Rikkokushi}}, {{ill|lt=Cheonan (Japan)|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=In the year 3 of Tenan|1=Ten'an}} ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), {{ill|lt=Yamato Province|Q907495|WD=Q907495|1=Yamato Province}}'s ``Great God'' |Shinkai|Q11591025}} is recorded to the effect that he was promoted from Juichii to Shoichii. At that time, only {{ill|lt=Kasuga Taisha|Q714559|WD=Q714559|1=Kasuga-taisha}} in Yamato Province reached the highest rank of Shoichii, which was an extremely early promotion nationwide, but the reason for this is not necessarily clear {{Sfn|Dainamochi Shrine (Shikiuchi)|1982}}{{Sfn|Dainamochi Shrine (Gods)|2000}}. One theory is that it was highly revered because it was an important transportation hub connecting the imperial capital of {{ill|lt=Nara Basin|Q10942269|WD=Q10942269|1=Nara Basin}} to Yoshino {{Sfn|Isenyama/Seyama (Heibonsha)|1981}}.{{ill|lt=extension (Era name)|Q1327274|WD=Q1327274|lt=Extended|1=Enchō}} 5 years ({{ill|lt=927 years|Q30470|WD=Q30470|1=927}}) “{{ill|lt=Engishiki|Q1342448|WD=Q1342448|1=Engishiki}}'' {{ill|lt=Engishiki Shinmyocho|Q11064932|WD=Q11064932|lt=Shinmyocho|1=Engishiki Jinmyōchō}}, in Yamato Province {{ill|lt=Yoshino District|Q1154558|WD=Q1154558|1=Yoshino District, Nara}}, ``Daimamochi Shrine Meishin University As a "Monthly Aijo Niiname", it is listed at {{ill|lt=Meishin Taisha|Q9610964|WD=Q9610964|1=Myōjin Taisha}} and the {{ill|lt=Monthly Festival|Q11516161|WD=Q11516161|1=Tsukinami-no-Matsuri}} and {{ill|lt=It is stipulated that at the Niinamesai|Q11581944|WD=Q11581944|1=Ainame Festival}} and {{ill|lt=Ninamesai|Q11501518|WD=Q11501518|1=Niiname-no-Matsuri}}, it is kept in a heihaku. Also, among the ``Engishiki'' special festivals, the ``Daimyo Mochimitama Shrine Troupe'' can be seen among the 285 Meishin Festivals in the Meishin Festival.

In the {{ill|lt=Middle Ages|Q12554|WD=Q12554|1=Middle Ages}} period, ``Imose Shrine'' can be seen in ``Okami Bunshin Rui Shrine Tsunami Tsukio'' {{Sfn|Dainamochi Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}.

In the {{ill|lt=early modern period|Q5308718|WD=Q5308718|1=Early modern period}} period, ``Yamatoshi'' shows {{ill|lt=Jinguji|Q1074971|WD=Q1074971|1=Jingū-ji}} Daikai-ji Temple (the location of the current shrine office) in the precincts, and a tidal pool in front of the shrine.{{Sfn|Dainamochi Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}{{Sfn|Dainamochi Shrine (Gods)|2000}}. It is said that the tide water gushes out from the Choobuchi, and purification was once performed there {{Sfn|Daimamochi Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}.After {{ill|lt=Meiji Restoration|Q8707|WD=Q8707|1=Meiji Restoration}}, it was ranked as {{ill|lt=Gosha|Q134917316|WD=Q134917316|1=Gō-sha}} in {{ill|lt=Modern shrine ranking system|Q712534|WD=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}.{{Sfn|Dainamochi Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}. {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|WD=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}}In the first year of the Meiji era, Daikai-ji Temple was abolished, the original Buddha and Buddhist utensils were moved to Bukkoku-ji Temple, and the Daihanya Sutra was moved to Unsen-ji Temple.{{Sfn|Dainamochi Shrine (Heibonsha)|1981}}.

=== God level ===
* {{ill|lt=Ten'an (Japan)|Q1075611|WD=Q1075611|lt=Ten'an|1=Ten'an}} January 27, 3rd year ({{ill|lt=859|Q23897|WD=Q23897|1=859}}), from Juichii to Shoichii ('{{ill|lt=Japan Sandai Jitsuroku|Q1052981|WD=Q1052981|1=Nihon Sandai Jitsuroku}}') - Written as 'Omi Kikami'.

